04853nam a22006975i 9780292794597DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212008txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927945977 a10.7560/7172992doi  a(DE-B1597)588797  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHQ1236.5.U6 ǂb P655 2008eb 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a976.40046800821 aGarcía, Sonia R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolíticas :bLatina Public Officials in Texas /cValerie Martinez-Ebers, Irasema Coronado, Patricia A. Jaramillo, Sharon A. Navarro, Sonia R. García. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (198 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Understanding Latina Political Leadership -- tChapter 2. Areas of Inquiry: Why So Few Latinas Hold Public Office -- tChapter 3. Irma Rangel: The First Latina in the Texas Legislature -- tChapter 4. Latinas in the Texas Senate -- tChapter 5. Latinas in Statewide Office -- tChapter 6. Latinas on the Bench -- tChapter 7. Latinas as Mayors -- tChapter 8. Latinas in Local Government -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix A. Tables—Latinas in Public Office -- tAppendix B. Interview Instrument -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decades since Latinas began to hold public office in the United States in the late 1950s, they have blazed new trails in public life, bringing fresh perspectives, leadership styles, and policy agendas to the business of governing cities, counties, states, and the nation. As of 2004, Latinas occupied 27.4 percent of the more than 6,000 elected and appointed local, state, and national positions filled by Hispanic officeholders. The greatest number of these Latina officeholders reside in Texas, where nearly six hundred women occupy posts from municipal offices, school boards, and county offices to seats in the Texas House and Senate. In this book, five Latina political scientists profile the women who have been the first Latinas to hold key elected and appointed positions in Texas government. Through interviews with each woman or her associates, the authors explore and theorize about Latina officeholders' political socialization, decision to run for office and obstacles overcome, leadership style, and representational roles and advocacy. The profiles begin with Irma Rangel, the first Latina elected to the Texas House of Representatives, and Judith Zaffirini and Leticia Van de Putte, the only two Latinas to serve in the Texas Senate. The authors also interview Lena Guerrero, the first and only Latina to serve in a statewide office; judges Linda Yanes, Alma Lopez, Elma Salinas Ender, Mary Roman, and Alicia Chacón; mayors Blanca Sanchez Vela (Brownsville), Betty Flores (Laredo), and Olivia Serna (Crystal City); and Latina city councilwomen from San Antonio, El Paso, Dallas, Houston, and Laredo.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexican American women politicianszTexas. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aCoronado, Irasema, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJaramillo, Patricia A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMadrid, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadrid, Patricia.1 aMartinez-Ebers, Valerie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71729940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794597/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL